  <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6">
    <blockquote>
      <p>Ingeniously nasty&#8230; reminiscent of Vladimir Nabokov and Patricia Highsmith&#8230; Expect to be provoked by a teasing metafictional game.</p>
      <footer>
        John Dugdale,
        <cite>
          <p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20190913131425/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/magazine/culture/need-to-know-karen-cleveland-anatomy-scandal-sarah-vaughan-the-wife-alafair-burke-consent-leo-benedictus-thrillers-review-p602w8ktl">The Sunday Times</a></p>
        </cite>
      </footer>
    </blockquote>
  </div>

  <div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6">
    <blockquote>
      <p>Creepily thought-provoking&#8230; [The narrator’s] manipulations are so cruel, his acts of violence so vile, that it feels profoundly disconcerting to have ever been seduced by him.</p>
      
      <footer>
        Melissa Broder,
        <cite>
          <p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20190913131425/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/29/books/review/read-me-leo-benedictus.html?smid=tw-nytbooks&amp;smtyp=cur">The New York Times</a></p>
        </cite>
      </footer>
	
    </blockquote>
  </div>
